.TH SDATA 1 "2026-04-10" "sdata 0.3.3" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
sdata \- statistical data interpreter for tabular data processing
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sdata
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ script ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sdata
is an interactive interpreter for data step\-based processing of tabular
datasets.
It is inspired by the Systat BASIC data step model and operates on a
two\-dimensional table of rows (records) and columns (variables).
.PP
When invoked without a script argument,
.B sdata
enters an interactive read\-eval\-print loop (REPL).
When a script file is provided it is executed non\-interactively and the
interpreter exits when the script completes.
.PP
Data can be read from and written to CSV, ODF, and OOXML (Excel) files.
A built\-in suite of statistical functions covers probability distributions,
aggregate statistics, and record navigation.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print a usage summary and exit.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Print the version string and exit.
.TP
.BI \-m " size"
Set the maximum number of rows the in\-memory data table may hold.
.TP
.BI \-t " count"
Set the maximum number of temporary variables per data step.
.TP
.BI \-\-clen " len"
Set the maximum length of character (string) variables in bytes.
.TP
.B \-\-noshell
Disable the
.B SYSTEM
command and the
.B SHELL()
function.
Useful in restricted or multi\-user environments.
.TP
.BR \-k ", " \-\-continue\-on\-error
Continue executing the script after a statement\-level error rather than
aborting.
The error message is printed to standard error and processing resumes with
the next statement.
.TP
.B \-\-ignore\-math\-errors
Instead of halting on a floating\-point domain error (e.g. LOG of a negative
number), emit a warning and return the missing value.
.TP
.BI \-o " file"
Redirect console output to
.IR file
in addition to standard output.
.TP
.B \-q
Quiet mode: suppress console output.
Error messages are still written to standard error.
.TP
.BI \-u ", " \-\-infmt " format"
Override the input dataset format.
Accepted values:
.BR CSV ", " ODF ", " OOXML .
.TP
.BI \-s ", " \-\-outfmt " format"
Override the output dataset format.
Accepted values:
.BR CSV ", " ODF ", " OOXML .
.SH LANGUAGE OVERVIEW
The
.B sdata
command language is statement\-based.
Statements fall into three categories:
.SS Declarative commands
Execute immediately and configure state for the next data step.
.RS
.TP
.B USE \fIfile\fR [\fB/FMT=\fIformat\fR] [\fB/NSCAN=\fIn\fR]
Load a dataset from a CSV, ODF, or OOXML file.
.TP
.B SAVE \fIfile\fR [\fB/FMT=\fIformat\fR] [\fB/HEADER=YES|NO\fR]
Queue the current data table to be saved after the next
.B RUN.
.TP
.B BY \fIvar\fR [\fIvar\fR ...]
Define BY\-group variables.
The indicators
.BR BOG() " and " EOG()
and the
.BR FIRST.\fIvar\fR " and " LAST.\fIvar
flags are set accordingly for each record.
Bare
.B BY
(no variables) cancels an active grouping.
.TP
.B SELECT \fIexpr\fR
Activate a row filter: only records for which
.I expr
is true are visible to subsequent data steps.
All record\-navigation functions
.RB ( RECNO ", " BOF ", " EOF ", " LAG ", " NEXT )
operate within the filtered (logical) view.
The filter is rebuilt automatically at the start of every
.BR RUN .
.TP
.B SELECT /ALL
Cancel the active row filter; all records become visible again.
.TP
.B SORT \fIvar\fR [\fIvar\fR ...]
Sort the data table on the named variables.
.TP
.B REPEAT \fIn\fR
Create
.I n
output records in the next data step (REPEAT mode).
.TP
.B FPATH \fIpath\fR /\fBUSE\fR|\fBSAVE\fR|\fBSUBMIT\fR|\fBOUTPUT\fR
Set the default directory for the specified file category.
.RE
.SS Immediate commands
Execute immediately; not part of the data step body.
.RS
.TP
.B RUN
Execute all deferred statements once per record (data step), then commit
the output table.
.TP
.B NEW
Clear the data table, all variables, the queued program, and any active
SELECT filter or BY grouping.
.TP
.B SORT \fIvar\fR [\fIvar\fR ...]
Re\-order the data table.
.TP
.B NAMES
List all permanent and temporary variables currently defined.
.TP
.B SUBMIT \fIfile\fR
Execute commands from an external script file (default extension
.BR .CMD ).
.TP
.B SYSTEM \fIcmd\fR
Run an external shell command.
Disabled by
.BR \-\-noshell .
.TP
.BR HELP " [\fItopic\fR | " /ALL ]
Display built\-in help.
Without an argument, list all commands and functions.
With
.B /ALL
print the full reference.
.TP
.BR QUIT " | " END
Exit the interpreter.
.RE
.SS Deferred statements
Queued between two
.B RUN
commands and executed once per record during the data step.
.RS
.TP
.B LET \fIvar\fR = \fIexpr\fR
Assign a permanent (table) variable.
.TP
.B SET \fIvar\fR = \fIexpr\fR
Assign a temporary variable (not written to the output table).
.TP
.B PRINT [\fIexpr\fR ...]
Print values to the console.
With no arguments, prints all permanent variables for the current record.
.TP
.B IF \fIcond\fR THEN \fIstmt\fR [ELSEIF \fIcond\fR THEN \fIstmt\fR] [ELSE \fIstmt\fR]
Conditional execution.
Block form (terminated by
.BR "END IF" )
is also supported.
.TP
.B SELECT [\fIexpr\fR] CASE \fIval\fR : \fIstmt\fR ... END SELECT
Multi\-way branch.
.TP
.B FOR \fIvar\fR = \fIstart\fR TO \fIend\fR [STEP \fIs\fR] ... NEXT
Counter\-controlled loop.
.TP
.B WHILE \fIcond\fR ... WEND
Condition\-controlled loop.
.TP
.B REPEAT ... UNTIL \fIcond\fR
Post\-test loop.
.TP
.B DELETE
Discard the current record; no output is written for it.
.TP
.B WRITE
Explicitly write the current PDV to the output table.
Suppresses the automatic end\-of\-record flush for that iteration.
.TP
.BR KEEP " | " DROP " \fIvar\fR [\fIvar\fR ...]"
Retain or remove columns from the output table after the next
.BR RUN .
.TP
.B HOLD [\fIvar\fR ...]
Retain variable values across records (instead of resetting to missing).
.TP
.B RENAME \fIold\fR=\fInew\fR [, \fIold\fR=\fInew\fR ...]
Rename columns.
.TP
.B ARRAY \fIname\fR \fIvar\fR [\fIvar\fR ...]
Create a virtual array providing indexed access to existing variables.
.TP
.B DIM \fIname\fR (\fIlo\fR TO \fIhi\fR) [/TEMP]
Create a numeric array with real storage.
Elements are initialised to missing.
.RE
.SH FUNCTIONS
Functions may appear anywhere in an expression.
Missing\-value propagation is automatic: if any required argument is missing
the result is missing, unless noted otherwise.
.SS Mathematical
.BR ABS (x),\  SQRT (x),\  EXP (x),\  LOG (x),\  LOG10 (x)
.br
.BR INT (x),\  CEIL (x),\  FLOOR (x),\  ROUND (x[,n]),\  MOD (x,y)
.SS Trigonometric
Radian variants:
.BR SIN ,\  COS ,\  TAN ,\  ATN ,\  ATAN2 ,\  SINH ,\  COSH ,\  TANH .
.br
Degree variants:
.BR SIND ,\  COSD ,\  TAND ,\  ATND ,\  ATAN2D .
.SS String
.BR LEN (s$),\  LEFT$ (s$,n),\  RIGHT$ (s$,n),\  MID$ (s$,start[,len])
.br
.BR TRIM$ (s$),\  UCASE$ (s$),\  LCASE$ (s$),\  POS (needle$,haystack$)
.br
.BR CHR$ (n),\  STR$ (x),\  NUM$ (x),\  VAL (s$),\  NUM (x)
.SS Base conversion
.BR HEX$ (n),\  OCT$ (n),\  BIN$ (n)
.SS Aggregate (row\-wise, across argument list)
.BR SUM ,\  MEAN ,\  STD ,\  VAR ,\  MIN ,\  MAX ,\  MEDIAN ,\  N ,\  NMISS
.PP
.B STD
and
.B VAR
use the sample formula (n\-1 denominator) and return missing when
fewer than two non\-missing values are supplied.
.SS Record navigation
All of the following operate in
.I logical
space when a
.B SELECT
filter is active; filtered\-out rows are invisible.
.TP
.BR RECNO ()
Current logical record number (1\-based).
.TP
.BR BOF ()
1 if this is the first visible record, else 0.
.TP
.BR EOF ()
1 if this is the last visible record, else 0.
.TP
.BR BOG ()
1 at the beginning of a BY group, else 0.
.TP
.BR EOG ()
1 at the end of a BY group, else 0.
.TP
.BI LAG( var [,n] )\ /\ LAGC$( var [,n] )
Value of
.I var
in the record
.I n
positions back (default 1).
Returns missing at a dataset or BY\-group boundary.
The variable name may be given unquoted:
.B LAG(X)
is equivalent to
.BR LAG(""X"") .
.TP
.BI NEXT( var [,n] )\ /\ NEXTC$( var [,n] )
Value of
.I var
in the record
.I n
positions ahead (default 1).
Returns missing at a dataset or BY\-group boundary.
.TP
.BI OBS( var ,row )\ /\ OBSC$( var ,row )
Value of
.I var
in the physical row
.I row
(1\-based, ignores the SELECT filter).
Returns missing if
.I row
is out of range.
.SS Conditional function
.BI IF( cond , true_val , false_val )
.br
Returns
.I true_val
when
.I cond
is non\-zero or non\-empty, else
.IR false_val .
.SS Special
.BR MISSING (x)
\(em 1 if x is missing, else 0.
.br
.BR RAN ()\ /\ RANDOM ()
\(em uniform random number in [0,\ 1).
.br
.BR DATE$ ()
\(em current date as
.IR YYYY\-MM\-DD .
.br
.BR TIME$ ()
\(em current time as
.IR HH:MM:SS .
.br
.BR SHELL( cmd$ )
\(em run a shell command; returns 0 on success (disabled by
.BR \-\-noshell ).
.SS Statistical distributions
Each distribution family provides four function variants.
The one\-letter prefix identifies the distribution; the suffix identifies
the variant:
.TP
.B DF
Probability density function (or probability mass function for discrete
distributions).
.TP
.B CF
Cumulative distribution function: P(X\ \(<=\ x).
.TP
.B IF
Inverse CDF (quantile function): value x such that P(X\ \(<=\ x)\ =\ p,
where 0\ <\ p\ <\ 1.
.TP
.B RN
Generate a random variate.
.PP
Available distribution families:
.TS
tab(|);
lb lb lb
l l l.
Prefix|Distribution|Parameters
Z|Standard Normal|none (mu=0, sigma=1)
N|Normal|\fImu\fR, \fIsigma\fR
U|Uniform|\fIlo\fR, \fIhi\fR
E|Exponential|\fIrate\fR
B|Beta|\fIa\fR, \fIb\fR (shape; no RN)
P|Poisson|\fIlambda\fR (discrete; k = integer)
G|Gamma|\fIshape\fR, \fIrate\fR
X|Chi\-square|\fIdf\fR
T|Student's t|\fIdf\fR
F|F distribution|\fIdf1\fR, \fIdf2\fR
M|Binomial|\fIn\fR, \fIprob\fR (discrete; no RN)
W|Weibull|\fIscale\fR, \fIshape\fR
L|Laplace|\fIloc\fR, \fIscale\fR
.TE
.PP
For each family the density/mass variant takes
.I x
(or
.I k
for discrete families) as its first argument, followed by the distribution
parameters.
The CDF and IDF variants have the same parameter order; the RN variant
takes only the distribution parameters.
.PP
Use
.B HELP DISTRIBUTIONS
from within
.B sdata
for a complete listing.
.SH FILE FORMATS
.TP
.B CSV
Comma\-separated values (default delimiter comma).
The delimiter can be changed with the
.B /DLM=
option on
.BR USE .
.TP
.B ODF / ODS
OpenDocument Spreadsheet (ISO/IEC 26300).
.TP
.B OOXML / XLSX
Office Open XML spreadsheet (ECMA\-376 / ISO/IEC 29500).
.PP
File format is auto\-detected from the file extension when not specified
explicitly.
Script files conventionally use the extension
.BR .CMD .
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Interactive session
.nf
$ sdata
sdata> use "sales.csv"
sdata> by region$
sdata> let total = price * qty
sdata> run
sdata> save "summary.csv"
sdata> quit
.fi
.SS Batch script
.nf
$ cat report.cmd
use "survey.csv"
select age >= 18
by state$
let income_k = income / 1000
print state$, mean(income_k), std(income_k), n(income_k)
run
save "report.csv"

$ sdata report.cmd
.fi
.SS Creating a synthetic dataset
.nf
$ sdata
sdata> repeat 100
sdata> let x = ran()
sdata> let y = 2*x + nrn(0, 0.1)
sdata> run
sdata> save "simdata.csv"
sdata> quit
.fi
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful completion.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred (parse error, file not found, unhandled exception, etc.).
